:: Wait. Could they? {"position":"800,975","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://images.armacad.info/blog_posts/blog_post_cover_image_24_1610176548.jpg"></img>

You decide to follow the link to this perfectly legal way of hosting PDFs online, and scroll through the citations and references. You notice a source that does not seem credible to you...

* [[Praagman. (2014)]]. "Dairy products and the risk of stroke and coronary heart disease: the Rotterdam Study." //European Journal of Nutrition//, 54(6), 981–990.

* [[Henrion, J. (1870)]]. //Bannana Quickstep//. D. P. Faulds. 

* [[Scragg, R. et. al. (2017)]]. "Effects of Monthly High-Dose Vitamin D Supplementation on Cardiovascular Disease in the Vitamin D Assessment Study : A Randomized Clinical Trial." //JAMA Cardiology//, 2(6), 608–616.  



:: blue {"position":"850,300","size":"100,100"}



:: citrus fruits {"position":"800,1475","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://www.teahub.io/photos/full/80-809726_fruit-splashing-in-water.jpg"></img>

Using multiple names for scurvy, or for any disease, in combination with "citrussy," a word any decent human being should never utter, is odd, but it is not a sign of misinformation.

You realize TikTok is exactly what you expected it to be.


:: drink water {"position":"1100,575","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://i.insider.com/61b8c75ac99fdc0019d584b0?width=1200&format=jpeg"></img>

You decide that water is the enemy and avoid drinking it, throwing out all your bottles.

This is not advisable, and you only last a day before becoming horribly dehydrated. 

//Click the arrow to the left of the text to return to the last choice.//


:: examine some more posts {"position":"800,725","size":"100,100"}
You send your results to Ambiorix.

Unfazed, he tells you that Vercingetorix has "some really good stuff out there," and that you should "check it out." 

Wanting to convince you, he shares a few tweets with you:

* "[[Soy]] contains phytoestrogen. Phyto-ESTROGEN. It's turning men into women and can destroy your hormones!"

* "[[Oranges]] contain vitamin C, vitamin C is particularly effective at fighting against scurvy!: (text-colour:green)[https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35818985/]"

* "RT (text-colour:green)[@AmerMedAssn]: [[Carrots]] are a good source of Vitamin A. They can give you night vision!"


:: raw meat {"position":"800,600","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://www.rollingstone.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/eating-raw-meat-trend.jpg?w=1581&h=1054&crop=1"></img>

That is correct. Raw meat does not, in fact, make people live forever.

The raw meat advice makes you very concerned about the rest of the health advice, but you want to make sure that you do your due diligence, perhaps it was a simple one time mistake. 

You begin to [[examine some more posts]].


